[{:post/body-markdown "## What Kotoba is\n\nKotoba is a small **Clojure-shaped language profile** for compiling\ncapability-checked programs to WebAssembly. It's aimed at code that should\nbe inspectable, portable, and constrained: AI-generated cells, sandboxed\nautomation, repository policy, and other untrusted programs where the host\ndecides which capabilities are available.\n\nThree things up front, since 'Clojure-shaped' invites the obvious pushback:\n\n1. **It's a Clojure-family *profile/subset*, not a full Clojure or\n   ClojureScript implementation.** Canonical source extension is `.kotoba`;\n   `.clj`, `.cljc`, and `.cljs` are accepted as compatibility formats. It is\n   not \"any JVM Clojure or ClojureScript program runs.\"\n2. **Compilation target is WebAssembly, compile-first.** The public surface\n   is `kotoba -e` / `kotoba wasm ...` -- not an interpreter with a Wasm\n   backend bolted on.\n3. **Capability-confined safety is the point, not an add-on.** Capabilities\n   are explicit, scoped, typed values (never ambient strings a module can\n   summon by name); a host-side guard intersects what a module was actually\n   handed against policy before any call runs.\n\n## 30-second tour\n\n```sh\nkotoba -e '(+ 1 2)'\nkotoba wasm build examples/hello.kotoba -o hello.wasm\nkotoba wasm safe-policy examples/policy-demo.kotoba\nkotoba wasm safe-build examples/policy-demo.kotoba --policy policy.edn -o policy-demo.wasm\n```\n\n## A few design notes\n\nThe compiler, CLI, and conformance tooling that process this Clojure-shaped\nlanguage are themselves written in Clojure/ClojureScript -- an earlier Rust\nimplementation was fully retired in favor of this CLJC authority.\n\nSafety is *benchmarked against* Rust, not copied from it: capability\nconfinement (deny-by-default, typed capabilities, signed audit receipts) is\ndesigned to exceed Rust-style memory safety alone, not just match it.\nRather than a full ownership/borrow/lifetime system, we shipped a narrow\naffine check scoped only to capability values -- a handle can be consumed\nat most once per execution path -- with a documented limitation instead of\na broader, harder-to-verify mechanism.\n\n## The rest of the stack\n\nAlongside the language, [`kotoba-lang/kotobase`](https://github.com/kotoba-lang/kotobase)\nplays the role Datomic plays for Clojure -- same datom/EAVT/Datalog model,\nbut reimagined for the distributed web: content-addressed blake3/CIDv1\nblocks instead of a single transactor over SQL/DynamoDB, a Prolly Tree\ninstead of a B-tree, an immutable commit DAG instead of a single log, and a\nCACAO-authenticated edge runtime instead of a JVM peer with a direct\nstorage connection.\n\n## Where to look\n\n- Language contract: https://github.com/kotoba-lang/kotoba-lang\n- Compiler/runtime (CLJC, Rust-free): https://github.com/kotoba-lang/kotoba\n- Distributed-web Datomic: https://github.com/kotoba-lang/kotobase\n\n## Question for this community\n\nWe shipped a narrow affine-typing check scoped only to capability values\ninstead of a general ownership/borrow system, on the reasoning that it's\nwhat the actual threat model needs and it's small enough to verify\nexhaustively. It has a documented gap (tracked per binding name, not per\nvalue) that doesn't weaken runtime enforcement but is a real limitation.\nWhere do you draw the line between \"ship the narrow useful slice, gaps\ndocumented\" and \"go build the complete thing first\"?", :post/created "2026-07-08", :post/open-question-to-seed-discussion "We shipped a narrow affine-typing check scoped only to capability values\n  instead of a general ownership/borrow system, on the reasoning that it's\n  what the actual threat model needs and it's small enough to verify\n  exhaustively. It has a documented gap (tracked per binding name, not per\n  value) that doesn't weaken runtime enforcement but is a real limitation.\n  Where do you draw the line between 'ship the narrow useful slice, gaps\n  documented' and 'go build the complete thing first'?", :post/title-recommended "[ANN] Kotoba: a Clojure-shaped language that compiles to WebAssembly, with capability-based safety (feedback wanted)", :post/body-markdown-ja "## Kotoba とは\n\nKotoba は capability-checked なプログラムを WebAssembly にコンパイルする、\n小さな **Clojure 形の言語プロファイル** です。AI 生成コード片・サンドボックス化\nされた自動化・その他ホスト側が capability を決める未信頼プログラムなど、検査\n可能・移植可能・制約されたコードを想定しています。\n\n最初に3点だけ('Clojure 形'と聞くと当然出てくる疑問への先回り):\n\n1. **Clojure ファミリーの *プロファイル/サブセット* であり、フルの Clojure /\n   ClojureScript 実装ではありません。** 正準な拡張子は `.kotoba`。`.clj` /\n   `.cljc` / `.cljs` は互換フォーマットとして受理されます。「JVM Clojure /\n   ClojureScript のプログラムなら何でも動く」わけではありません。\n2. **コンパイル先は WebAssembly、compile-first です。** 公開インターフェース\n   は `kotoba -e` / `kotoba wasm ...` — Wasm バックエンドを後付けした\n   インタプリタではありません。\n3. **capability に閉じ込められた安全性が本体で、後付けの機能ではありません。**\n   capability は明示的・スコープ付き・型付きの値であり、モジュールが名前で\n   勝手に呼び出せる ambient な文字列ではありません。呼び出しの前にホスト側の\n   ガードが「実際に渡されたもの」をポリシーと突き合わせます。\n\n## 30秒ツアー\n\n```sh\nkotoba -e '(+ 1 2)'\nkotoba wasm build examples/hello.kotoba -o hello.wasm\nkotoba wasm safe-policy examples/policy-demo.kotoba\nkotoba wasm safe-build examples/policy-demo.kotoba --policy policy.edn -o policy-demo.wasm\n```\n\n## 設計上の補足\n\nこのClojure形言語を処理するコンパイラ・CLI・conformance ツール群自体が\nClojure/ClojureScript で書かれています — 以前あった Rust 実装は完全に撤去し、\nこの CLJC 実装が正本になりました。\n\n安全性は Rust を**参考にした**のではなく、Rust に対して**ベンチマークして\n上回ることを狙って**設計されています: capability confinement（deny-by-default、\n型付き capability、署名済み監査レシート）は、Rust 流のメモリ安全性だけを\n上回ることを目指しています。汎用的な所有権/借用/lifetime システムの代わりに、\ncapability の値だけに限定した狭い affine チェックを採用しました — ハンドルは\n実行パスごとに高々一度しか消費できません。より広く検証しづらい仕組みの代わりに、\n限界を明記した狭いチェックを選びました。\n\n## スタックの残り\n\n言語のほかに、[`kotoba-lang/kotobase`](https://github.com/kotoba-lang/kotobase)\nが Clojure に対する Datomic の役割を果たします — 同じ datom/EAVT/Datalog\nモデルですが、分散webのために再設計されています: 単一のtransactor + SQL/\nDynamoDB ではなく blake3/CIDv1 のコンテンツアドレス方式、B-tree ではなく\nProlly Tree、単一ログではなく immutable な commit DAG、直接ストレージ接続を\n持つ JVM peer ではなく CACAO 認証された edge runtime、という違いです。\n\n## 参照先\n\n- 言語コントラクト: https://github.com/kotoba-lang/kotoba-lang\n- コンパイラ/ランタイム(CLJC、Rust-free): https://github.com/kotoba-lang/kotoba\n- 分散webのDatomic: https://github.com/kotoba-lang/kotobase\n\n## このコミュニティへの質問\n\n汎用的な所有権/借用システムの代わりに、capability の値だけに限定した狭い\naffine チェックを採用しました — これは実際の脅威モデルが要求するものであり、\nかつ網羅的に検証しきれる規模に収まるという判断です。既知のギャップも1つ\nあります(束縛名単位の追跡であり値のprovenance単位ではないため、runtime側の\nenforcementは弱めないものの実在する限界です)。「制約を明記した上で狭く\n有用なスライスを出す」のと「まず完全なものを作ってから出す」の境界を、\n皆さんはどこに引きますか?", :post/posted-at "2026-07-08", :post/title-rationale "Deliberately says 'Clojure-shaped', not 'Clojure' or 'Clojure on Clojure',\n  in the title -- that framing belongs in the body where it can be\n  explained, not in the title where it reads as a claim to litigate. The\n  '[ANN]' prefix matches the real convention observed in Showcase's recent\n  topics ('[ANN] Quandary', '[ANN Preview] PluMCP 0.2.0') -- not invented,\n  copied from what other announcement posts on this forum actually do.", :post/replies "[{:date \"2026-07-12\", :in-reply-to \"jackrusher\", :in-reply-to-comment \"This text reads like it was written by Claude.\", :body-markdown \"Ha, fair catch! You're right -- I'm not a confident English writer, so I do lean on Claude to help me draft posts like this one. The design, the code, and the ideas behind Kotoba are mine, but I use it as a writing assistant to make sure the English reads clearly. Sorry if that came across as impersonal -- happy to answer any questions directly here in my own (rougher) words if that's more useful!\"}]", :post/status :live, :post/title-options ["[ANN] Kotoba: a Clojure-shaped language that compiles to WebAssembly, with capability-based safety (feedback wanted)" "[ANN] Kotoba: capability-safe Wasm compilation for a Clojure-family source profile -- design feedback wanted" "[ANN] A Clojure-shaped, Wasm-targeting language for sandboxing untrusted/AI-generated code -- looking for design critique"], :post/id "kotoba-clojureverse-launch", :post/posted-note "Posted to ClojureVerse (Showcase) and cleared review -- topic is live at\n                    :post/url. First reply (jackrusher) observed the post reads as\n                    Claude-assisted; replied acknowledging that (see :post/replies).", :db/id -1, :post/url "https://clojureverse.org/t/ann-kotoba-a-clojure-shaped-language-that-compiles-to-webassembly-with-capability-based-safety-feedback-wanted/14949", :post/ready-note "Both publish-gate items closed 2026-07-08. Body-markdown\n                   rewritten to state each as shipped (with its documented\n                   scope/limitation), not as roadmap. Do one final read\n                   before posting to confirm no stale phrasing slipped\n                   through.", :post/target "{:site \"clojureverse.org\", :category \"Showcase\", :category-correction \"An earlier draft of this plan named a category ('Community News',\\n   explicitly avoiding 'Show and Tell') that does NOT exist on\\n   ClojureVerse -- an unverified guess, not checked against the actual\\n   forum. The real top-level categories (fetched from\\n   clojureverse.org/categories, 2026-07-08) are: Community Center,\\n   Questions & Help, Showcase, Learning Resources, Topics, Projects, The\\n   Fringe, Clojure Sustainability Works. There is no announcements/news\\n   category distinct from Showcase.\", :category-rationale \"Showcase is where library/language [ANN] posts actually go on this\\n   forum -- confirmed from its real recent topics, which include '[ANN]\\n   Quandary' (a Clojure DSL), '[ANN Preview] PluMCP', and 'Clua 0.1.1 --\\n   safe execution of untrusted Lua scripts in Clojure' (close in spirit to\\n   Kotoba: a constrained/sandboxed execution story). The forum explicitly\\n   welcomes 'genuine instead of spammy' self-promotion there -- framing the\\n   post as an announcement with real design questions attached fits the\\n   norm, rather than avoiding the category altogether.\", :sequencing \"Post here first; incorporate whatever critique lands before\\n               cross-posting to r/ProgrammingLanguages, Lobsters, or\\n               Show HN -- don't debut the same rough edges twice.\"}", :post/posting-guidance ["Category: Showcase -- verified against clojureverse.org/categories, where [ANN] library/language posts actually go on this forum." "Title says 'Clojure-shaped', never 'Clojure on Clojure' or bare 'Clojure' -- that framing lives in the body." "First 3 lines state what's different (profile/subset, Wasm compile-first, capability-confined safety) before anything else." "Include at least one runnable code block (the 30-second tour)." "End with one concrete, answerable question (the narrow-slice-vs-complete-feature tradeoff) to drive replies." "Link kotoba-lang/kotoba-lang (the contract) before kotoba-lang/kotoba (the implementation) -- resolve 'what is this' before 'how does it run'." "Only cross-post to r/ProgrammingLanguages / Lobsters / Show HN after incorporating ClojureVerse feedback."], :post/blocked-by "[{:item \"Rust-style borrow checker (S2 layer)\", :ref \"kotoba-lang/kotoba-lang docs/adr/ADR-safe-capability-language.md, status table\", :state :done, :done-note \"Shipped 2026-07-08 as a deliberately NARROW slice, not a\\n               general Rust-style ownership/borrow/lifetime system: affine\\n               typing scoped ONLY to capability-typed values (deterministic\\n               drop, no implicit clone -- kotoba-lang/kotoba\\n               kotoba.runtime/cap-affine-problems, :cap-value-reused). A\\n               full ownership analysis was deliberately rejected -- per the\\n               ADR's own safety ladder it would only reach \\\"A grade\\\",\\n               below the capability-confinement (S grade) target already\\n               shipped; T1 Memory Safety was already achieved without a\\n               borrow checker (free-less allocator + bounds checks + no\\n               concurrency primitives). Documented conservative\\n               false-negative: tracking is per local binding name, so\\n               renaming through a let-alias and using both names once each\\n               is an uncaught reuse -- does not weaken runtime confinement\\n               (T3), since every use still re-resolves through\\n               kotoba.cap-table/resolve-use regardless of alias.\"} {:item \".cljs reinstated as an accepted compatibility source extension\", :ref \"kotoba-lang/kotoba-lang docs/adr/ADR-kotoba-lang-profile.md addendum (2026-07-08); profile v3\", :state :done, :done-note \"Shipped 2026-07-08 across three repos: kotoba-core-contracts\\n               gained a :cljs source-kind (resources/kotoba/lang/\\n               source_contract.edn) mirroring .clj's shape -- single-target\\n               (:reader-target :cljs), NOT the fully portable .cljc branch\\n               chain, so a .cljs file cannot carry #?(:kotoba ...) branches\\n               any more than a .clj file can. kotoba-lang/kotoba bumped its\\n               pin and added src/demo.cljs as a genuine end-to-end positive\\n               fixture (a bare .cljs FILE, not .cljc read under\\n               --reader-target cljs, defaulting to the :cljs target with no\\n               flag needed). kotoba-lang/kotoba-lang bumped profile.edn to\\n               v3, added a dated ADR addendum documenting the reversal\\n               (the v2 retirement rested on a thin equivalence argument\\n               with no porting-friction analysis), and added a positive\\n               conformance fixture with expect-values verified against the\\n               real implementation, not just asserted.\"}]"}]